I mapped a 32-bit multiplier to an UltraScale+ FPGA, but Vivado is showing terrible Fmax (under 80 MHz). How do I optimize this for DSP slice pipelining?
module mult32 (input clk, input [31:0] a, b, output reg [63:0] p);
  always @(posedge clk) p <= a * b;
endmodule

output:
### Functional Explanation
This module performs a 32x32-bit multiplication and registers the 64-bit product. Since it happens internally in a single clock cycle, it places immense pressure on the combinational multiplier logic.

### Potential Issues
1. **Unpipelined DSP Chains**: A 32x32 multiplication cannot fit into a single DSP48E2 slice (which natively supports 27x18 multiplication). Therefore, the synthesis tool cascades multiple DSP slices and fabric logic to calculate the 64-bit product. Because there are no internal pipeline registers, the signal must propagate through the entire cascaded chain in one clock cycle, drastically reducing the Maximum Frequency (Fmax).

### Recommended Fix
To achieve high Fmax, you must provide pipeline registers on the inputs, internally within the multiplication (if cascading), and on the output. Modern synthesis tools can automatically absorb these registers into the DSP blocks (yielding 3+ levels of latency).
```verilog
module mult32_pipelined (input clk, input [31:0] a, b, output reg [63:0] p);
  // Input registers
  reg [31:0] a_reg, b_reg;
  // Intermediate pipeline registers
  reg [63:0] p_pipe1, p_pipe2;

  always @(posedge clk) begin
    // Stage 1: INMODE / A / B Registers
    a_reg <= a;
    b_reg <= b;
    // Stage 2: M (Multiplier) Registers
    p_pipe1 <= a_reg * b_reg;
    // Stage 3: P (Product cascaded) Registers
    p_pipe2 <= p_pipe1;
    // Stage 4: Fabric matching
    p <= p_pipe2;
  end
endmodule
```

### Timing / Synthesis Considerations
Adding 3-4 clock cycles of latency is standard for 32+ bit multipliers in FPGAs running at >250MHz. To force the synthesis tool to utilize dedicated DSP registers rather than slice flip-flops, you can wrap the registers in attributes like `(* use_dsp = "yes" *)`. The result will show a massive reduction in logic levels in the critical path (from ~8 down to 0-1).

